nodes.title: Note on all masks
widgets_values:
All of this is to make a more refined very fainted "aura" outline blur mask on the character so the normal inpaint performs better and avoid superposition on denoise. 

Might be completely unecessery for inpainting control-net but I already had this done for another workflow, so why not.

YOu can tinker with the blue nodes values here

Most of the times you don't want to end up with the inpainted prompt and seed recorded to your final inpainted image since the original image composition is normally more important.

So if you want to preserve your original image prompts, LoRas used, seed, CFG, Steps, etc, use these groups.  

It will process the LoRas on the prompt by the "ImpactWildcardProcessor" node and will add manual LoRas with 12 characters (AutoV3). 

If the LoRa was not on the prompt, you might want to add the Autov3 manually.

"Automatic" (green) takes precendent over "Manual" (orange) inputs. If you want to input manualy mute the automatic group.

Automatic need you to load/upload your image here again and run the workflow. The metadata won't show up until you queue. You still need to load the image on the "Load image and mask" groups

Of course if your image to be inpainted is not AI generated, all these groups to retrieve the old metadata would mean nothing so you can just mute them all.

YOU NEED TO MUTE THIS GROUP if your are not going to retrieve or add info because if you let this on the prompt will be empty.

Want to add any manual models hash? put them here (comma separated AutoV3 hashes).

 → → → → → → → → → → → → →

← You should ALWAYS composite at the risk of degrading your whole image if you don't. BUT sometimes you don't care and the image blends better without it, so here it's the option.

Obs: Area inPaint will always composite no matter this option.

This math expressions will make sure the new outpainted image is devisible by 8. The ksampler don't deal with images that are not and will change the resolution. The composite in the end would look missmatched without this.

Sometimes, outpainting can result in poor blending, even when not compositing or using Flux Fill. Especially when working with images that have a uniform background or plain borders, like a solid blue sky.

To improve the blending quality you can increase the feathering and blur on the outpainting mask.

Keep in mind that raising these values will change more of the original image, as the adjustments create a smoother transition inpainting the border areas.

You can modify these settings below: ↓ ↓ ↓ ↓ ↓ ↓ ↓

Keep Depth and Canny Flux Tool loras loaded here at all the time. 
Keep in mind:
❗❗ It will not work with Flux Fill ❗❗

The workflow will turn them OFF automatically if you chose Flux Fill for inpainting

NOTE ON GUDANCE →→→→

"Flux Fill" likes 30 guidance so, this workflow will add automatically 26.5 (because 3.5 + 26.5 = 30) to whatever guidance you choose IF using Flux Fill. So no need to adjust guidance just because you are using the "Flux Fill model"

On v6.1 I added the possibility so you can change this additional guidance

nodes.title: How to make loops
widgets_values:
To make a loop:

1- Write in your prompt two or more prompts separated by "&&" (without quotation marks).
2- Each prompt will be assigned to a segmented mask in the mask order previwed here. 
3- Run the workflow. It will generate a number of images equal to the number of segmented masks/prompts. It will generate a whole image for each mask/loop so each prompt is its own thing. It works with "area inpainting" and everything else, but "outpainting" is not recommended because it will outpaint for each segmented mask, which makes no sense. Best to outpaint first and inpaint with loops after it.

IF you have batch bigger than 1 AND The "Image Chooser" (located on the "Loops Compositing" group, near the end) turned ON, you need to pick each image of each step. You can also leave it off and the first image of each step will be selected.

4- Finally, your composite image will be saved.

nodes.title: Notes on segmented masks for loops
widgets_values:
Loops are only triggered IF you have multiple prompts on the main prompt devided by "&&". If not, these segmented masks won't be used.

Here you can check how many segmented masks (green preview) your mask (blue preview) was devided into automatically. 

Masks are segmented automatically following this order: always right to left first, then up to down... →↓

nodes.title: Notes on Loops compositing!!! READ. Choose your image.
widgets_values:
All processes within this group will only be used or saved if loops are present in the prompt. If not, they will be bypassed, and the workflow will proceed as usual. BUT❗❗ there is an important exception:

Even without any loops in your prompt, the "Image Chooser" node WILL PAUSE your workflow and require you to select an image, even thogh it won't matter. Using no loops will always save all your batch images, but the node will pause and prompt you to choose if left ON.

There is a node called "Control Bridge" that can enforce a bypass based on a boolean condition, which can be useful in such cases. However, I did not use it because it creates additional issues, particularly with loop counts. So this needs to be done mannualy.

In summary, keep it OFF (bypassed) if you are not using loops If you are using loops with batches, keep it ON to select each result from each step.

Just a reminder, to make a loop:
1- Write in your prompt two or more prompts separated by "&&" (without quotation marks).
2- Each prompt will be assigned to a segmented mask. Masks are segmented automatically following this order: right, down... →↓
3- Run the workflow. It will generate a number of images equal to the number of segmented masks/prompts. It will generate a whole image for each mask/loop so each prompt is its own thing. It works with "area inpainting" and everything else, but "outpainting" is not recommended because it will outpaint for each segmented mask, which makes no sense. Best to outpaint first and inpaint with loops after it.

IF you have batch bigger than 1 AND The "Image Chooser" ON you need to pick each image of each step. You can also leave it off and the first image of each step will be selected. If you choose 2 images, only the first choice will be used.

4- Finally, your composite image will be saved.

nodes.title: How visible should the "aura" around the mask be? More is MORE visible
How much to expand the AURA

widgets_values:
I decided to add Fill to outpainted areas even if you decide to not use fill to the inpainted areas, because it makes outpainting with different denoise values perform better.

With inpainting, you might want to preserve what is inside the inpainted area with a lower denoise.

For outpainting it makes no sense to preserve a black or gray padded area. So fill always makes sense.

Notes on Loop prompts and Shedule LoRas
widgets_values:
This Node here ↑↑ will allow your prompt to have additional LoRa syntax directly written on it and applied here, and if using loops, each loop can have its own lora by doing this.

Read about LoRa schedule syntax here: https://github.com/asagi4/comfyui-prompt-control/blob/master/doc/syntax.md

Exemple: <lora:Shrek:0.7> [<lora:tattoo_flux:0.8>::0.4]

This will have Sh LoRA applied at 0.7 strength throughout the generation, while tattoo_flux will be applied at 0.8 strength until 40% of the generation, after which tattoo_flux will be removed.

Keep in mind, adding or removing LoRas with schedule have an impact in the generation time.

LoRas added by the below group (LoRas - Optional) ↓↓ will be ALWAYS On at all the time on all the loops.

Even if you are going to use a GGUF Flux model (in that case, change the switch input), 

Please select the base flux1-dev model on the "Load Diffusion Model" above ↑↑↑

That model name is going to be used to save in the image metadata so yout images get cross-posted on That Flux Dev model.

nodes.title: Turn ON resize? Final image will be smaller

widgets_values: Here it calculates the lowest divisible by 8 resolution and crops the image, taking the extra pixels out. This method instead of resizing is better because the image won't lose any quality, as resizing even by a pixel can damage the original quality. The image will be composited back to the original res at the end of the workflow. (Inpainting ONLY)
### If you choose both, you will end up with Nunchacku

### On model Downloads:
My workflow won't error out if you don't load a model. So you don't need to download all models, just the ones you would like to use.

Still, when using GGUF you need to at least load a Flux Dev model if you want the output to have Civitai Metadata pointing to Flux because `Image Saver` does not support GGUF, so it saves the metadata from the Flux Dev model.

To understand this mess
widgets_values:
This is confusing, but basically if Outpainting is Off, it gets normal context mask, if On it gets a outpadded context mask so it doesn't missmatch.
And then after that is another check:
If using loops turn outpainting off: it gets normal context mask

The idea is to use Flux Tools (lora, Detph or Canny) conditioning only at some steps (time stamp) and after that it fallsback to the default (without PixtoPix cond/lora depth or canny)

This creates another level of control on top of LoRa weight.

You can control when LoRa FluxTools start and ends AND the LoRA weight (on the LoRa load section). 

I recommend to leave lora at 0.75 or increase it to 0.8-0.9 only if you remove conditioning here at lower steps (end at 0.10 or 0.28). But even then, unfortunantly the LoRa is not removed with the conditioning, only the conditioning, and at high weigth the LoRA will degrade the generation a little. SO it's better to just leave it at 0.75. The effect is strong and good enough.

Notes on Pass_Back
widgets_values:
The pass_back feature allows each loop iteration to feed its output into the next generation, ensuring that changes accumulate progressively.

Without pass_back, each segmented mask is generated independently of the previous loop's result, and everything is combined at the end.

The default setting will be ON.

Cache Speedup sucks for Flux Fill ❗❗ It's ok for Alimama.

Turn it off or at least use negative Thresholding fo Flux Fill.

nodes.title: Note on Cache Speedup for Nunchaku
widgets_values:
Cache Speedup for Nunchaku needs to be set on the Nunchaku Model Load node itself ❗❗ 

It will error out if you leave this enable and use nunchaku.

You can bypass "FluxKontextImageScale" ↑ node if you have the VRAM. 

It scales the reference to a smaller one for Kontext. But you can load large references if you have VRAM, as far as I have tested.

Also you can have a mask mismatch if you leave this on

→→→→
THIS NODE IS MEANT TO BE USED only when using "Localized Inpaiting" (see that option in the CONTROL ROOM):

Load the same image here as the main one (needs to be the same size) and make a SECOND mask. It should be the area you want to have as context.

This will make the inpainting not use the full image but the "inpainted area" + "this context mask" as the image area. It will use the "✂️ Inpaint Crop & Stitch" nodes. 

The "Localized Inpainting" can save you generation time if your whole image is too big. It will always inpaint at 1024 max.

- right click > open mask editor

You can load a black and white previously saved mask (external mask) as well. If you do, change the switch to true. 

This is NOT the inpainted area, it's te "context" area. But it can include the inpainting area as well, it's not a problem.

Example: I want to inpaint only the eyes but have the whole face as context. Mask the eyes on the magenta main load image node and here on the yellow "load image" you mask the whole face.

If you are going to load a previously saved black and white mask (external mask), use this loader (pale_blue) and set the switch to TRUE →→→→→→→→→→→→→→→

Even if not loading an external mask. You might need to leave any loaded image here just so you don't get a warning.

# Changelog
---
## \[v10.0.0] - 10/10/25
### ➕ New - Nunchaku!

1. ❗ Completely overhaul of the expanded workflow distribution. It was too cluttered, so I've expanded it to make more room for the nodes.

2. Nunchaku support! You can now use Nunchaku or GGUF for all three options> Normal Flux (alimama inpainting); Flux Fill; Kontext

3. You can leave mask empty to send the whole image to be inpainted/edited. Good for Kontext full image change.


What was Changed: 
- Fast bypasser is now a fast muter. It's better, 'Any Switch (rgthree)' works more reliably. 
- Better organization
- Removed Force VAE and Force Text Encoder. It was causing crashes

Known "Bugs": 
- Any Nunchaku model won't work with cache speed up option.
---

## \[v9.0.2] - 12/09/25
### 🐞 Bug Fix

1. ❗ New comfyUI/frontend breaks Get/Set bypassed nodes and 'Any Switch (rgthree)' won't work anymore with mismatched types whis bypassed groups. This is a fast fix, sorry for taking this long. I still intend to do a new rewroked version with Nunchaku support.

What was Changed: 
- get vae from both ksamplers moved out of group
- Get_inpaint_mask and Get_DepthOrCanny moved out of outpainiting group
- I had to add Big Contex Switch instead of Any switch in the ouptainting mask output and contex mask ouput for area inpainting.
- Add Context instead of Any Switch right after ksampler VAE decode.

---

## \[v9.0.1] - 30/06/25
### 🐞 Bug Fix

1. ❗ I have completely forgot about the "ReferenceLatent" when I uploaded v9.0 for using Kontext. That is the reason it was giving bad results for many people. It should be giving way better results now. I also added the stitch option to add a second reference image.


---

## \[v9.0.0] - 27/06/25
### ➕ New

1. ❗ Added Inicial Flux Kontext support!

  * You can now load a 4th model option and inpaint using Flux Kontext!
  * It works with positive prompt with direct orders, [read the guide here](https://docs.bfl.ai/guides/prompting_guide_kontext_i2i).
  * As of right now **it does NOT** work with Flux Tools Depth or Canny and it won't work with Alimama Control-net. So those are disable automatically when you choose Flux Kontext.
  * Flux Kontext likes 2.5 guidance. So I automatically deducted -1 from the normal standard guidance when you choose Kontext.
  * **IT WORKS** with masks, so you don't need to send the whole image (but you can). It works with Loops! (it's really nice, please test it), with negative thresholding (to some extent), outpainting (order it to outpaint), Daemon Detailer, Aura mask, and everything else the workflow does. 

    * This means you can inpaint with localized area mask and it won't VAE degrade your image. 

    * Keep in mind, If you send the whole image, it will suffer from consecutive inpaintings VAE degradation.  

---

## \[v8.12]
### 🐞 Bug Prevention

1. Remove dependencies (no longer needed) cutom_nodes:
   * [Crystools](https://github.com/crystian/ComfyUI-Crystools) > changes all swithc nodes to index switch
   * [Logic](https://github.com/theUpsider/ComfyUI-Logic) > I had missed one Float node on Control-Panel

2. Resize Mask (context mask) will error out, node #1834, on v8.11 I have changed mask resize to use lanczos, but it is bugged, so I changed that to other method like bicube. let's wait for the dev to fix it
---
## \[v8.11]
1. Change downscale (resize) interpolation from nearest (terrible quality) > Lazcos

---

## \[v8.1] - 06/06/25

### 🐞 Bug Prevention

1. ❗ Outpainting will be automatically disabled, even if remains enabled on the control panel, when using Loops. This occurs because loops pass back the image during each iteration, expanding/outpainting it on top of the previous one. This process results in a mismatch in the final composite.

### ➕ New

* 🔹 COMPACT updated to v8.1 (loops etc)

---

## \[v8.0] - 27/05/25

### ➕ New

* 🔹 Making Loops!

  * ❗ Read the notes scattered on the workflow to see how to make loops. Basic usage: separate prompts with `&&`.
  * • New custom node `loop-image` to support loops.
  * • Added group “Loop segmented mask control” to preview segmented masks.
  * • Nodes to check/filter loops in the positive prompt and apply conditioning.
* 🔹 Batch Image Chooser

  * ❗ Choose which image to process in a batch via the “image chooser” node.
  * • Added group “Loops Compositing” for batch compositing with preview images.
* 🔹🔹 Prompt Control Enhancements

  * • Added text encoder and LoRa scheduling:

    * `PC: Schedule LoRAs` node
    * `PC: Schedule Prompt (positive)` node

### 🐞 Bug Fixes

* 🔹🔹🔹 Outpainting: Because of the AE refactoring to set/get I need to mute the second composite instead of bypass since "Get" original image gets it no matter if it is bypassed or not, so it always delivers the original to the switch node, thus, saving the original image instead of the oupainted one. Muting the group fixes it.

## \[v7.2] - 06/05/25

### ➕ New

1. ❗ Option to invert aura direction. Useful when inpainting the whole background leaving a small area to not change, in this cases the aura grows OUT of the not painted area, not inside it. Another way to put it: a black aura grows inside the inpainted area when this is ON.
Use case: if you want to inpaint the BG and leave the charcater, but want the Ksampler to understand the boundaries of said character, using a very fainted "black" aura makes the ksampler to keep the surrounding area in the beggining while slowly painting it over the denoising process since it is a gray area. (turn on ksampler preview so you can see this happening). 
Recommended settings: Low visibility (30) with a small grow (5).  


### 🔄 Refactoring

  * ❗ New group for loading each LoRA model with recommended strength 0.75.
  * ❗ Control-room toggles: Depth vs Canny.

  * ❗ Localized area option for Canny/Depth outpainting.

* 🔹🔹🔹 Workflow Cleanup & Improvements:

  1. Improved ✂️ Inpaint Crop (now auto-muted outside COMPACT).
  2. LoRA Stacker via LoraManager node.
  3. Fixed GrowMask 5px for outpainting blend.
  4. Slider for Image Resize Resolution.
  5. Custom node cleanup: replaced crystools switches with easy-use.
  6. Logic operators updated to easy-use.
  7. Inpaint Stitch moved outside localized group (auto-muted).

  9. Enhanced negative prompt saving logic.

10. Improved prompt reader for SAM Detector metadata retrieval.

## \[v7.0]

### ➕ New

* 🔹 Flux Tools LoRA Depth & Canny "control-net" support
  (Works with Alimama — ❗❗ it will **NOT** work with Flux Fill ❗❗)

  * ❗ a) Add new group for Loading each LoRA model.

    * They should be loaded all the time and will be dynamically used.
    * You can control each LoRA strength — recommended: **0.75**
  * ❗ b) New toggles on the control-room group:

    * Choose between **Depth OR Canny** (not both)
  * ❗ c) Depth and LoRA groups for LoRA InstructPixToPixConditioning:

    * Allows you to choose when Depth or Canny will start and stop
    * Conditioning falls back to standard **Alimama inpainting**
  * d) New group for preprocessing the image for Depth or Canny
  * e) Canny or Depth reference image for Outpainting:

    * **Depth**: fast-fill in a more complex way
    * **Canny**: pads outpainting with black
  * f) Canny or Depth works with **localized area** option

* 🔹🔹 New: Aura Mask implemented back on the COMPACT workflow with convenient easy-to-use toggle and sliders.

* 🔹🔹🔹 A bunch of smaller Changes:

  1. Fixed old to new “✂️ Inpaint Crop (Improved)”
  2. LoAd Loras: now using "Lora Stacker (LoraManager)" node
     → It’s better and everyone should use LoraManager — fantastic custom node
  3. Fixed: “GrowMask” 5 px not connected on the outpainting fast-fill for better blending
  4. Added a slider for “Image Resize Resolution”
  5. Nodes cleanup:
     → Replaced some “crystools” switch nodes with “easy-use” switches
     → Reducing dependency on custom nodes (some “crystools” may remain)
     → Same gradual cleanup plan for “Logic” nodes
     → Updated control-room logic nodes to “easy-use”
  6. “Logic operator” > “easy-use” for negative thresholding
     → Uses index instead of bool
  7. “Logic operator” > “easy-use” for localized area inpainting
     → Uses index instead of bool
  8. “✂️ Inpaint Stitch (Improved)” moved outside localized area inpainting group (not on COMPACT)
     → It is now auto-muted by a muter
  9. “Get LoRAs names and process it do Get metadata” group updated:
     → Evaluates if LoRAs are in use in a different way
     → Adds clean LoRA names to the positive prompt with 🖌️ and 🎯 for full LoRA syntax
  10. Fixed saving negative prompt on metadata: will first save the retrieved original negative prompt and if that is OFF, it will only save inpainting negative **IF** using thresholding.
  11. It will always evaluate if Positive is empty (if retrieving the original positive prompt fails) and if it is, it uses the inpainting prompt to save in the metadata.
  12. Fixed: for COMPACT: "SD Prompt Reader" won't error when retrieving loaded image original metadata that used **SAM Detector** to make a mask.
